I don't blame them for not trying... To be honest, the people who still want a Youtube Rewind should be lucky that they got one cause if I was the one making decisions on Youtube, there would be no Youtube Rewind 2019, 2020 or Youtube Rewind anything in the future. Even when it was still good, I never really saw the point of it, even when people were raving about it.


Edit: Also, I know everybody is going to disagree with me on this, but as someone who is planning on starting a proper youtube channel next year, I'm actually excited for the new Youtube. I don't think it's going to be that big of a problem at all actually. BECAUSE NOW YOU'RE ALLOWED TO BE INAPPROPRIATE AGAIN!! I've listened to many youtubers complaints and personally, I don't see what's the problem. This is what people have been wanting for a long time, why are we sad that they're allowing us to be vulgar again next year? If there really is anybody being punished, it's the child friendly people who we should be feeling sorry for... But I don't know... I've been thinking about streaming on Twitch instead of youtube for sometime so... I'm just saying, I think that if Youtube can do this Coppa thing properly, it could actually benefit everybody, especially since they already allow us to age restrict our own content.

snippet.textDisplay:
I posted this on the Rewind video and I still think it's true -

Dear YouTube,

Get a creator or a group of creators on YouTube to direct your Rewind videos. You're business people, which is evidenced by how last year you spent a lot of money directing a tone deaf commercial directed at people who already use YouTube and this year your stand-out play it safe idea was to save money on production by letting the number of views on your videos dictate the content of your Rewind creation.

There's a reason there's a disconnect between the people that run YouTube (you) and the people that use YouTube (creators) and as Rewind's progress it's becoming ever more evident that the divide is growing not shrinking. We get it. You're a business but you don't just rely on creatives they are the foundation stone for the bridge that transports money from corporations with advertising campaigns to people that watch creators.

You are the architects and custodians of that bridge and it is showing signs of wear and tear. Your maintenance cannot focus on what goes across the bridge, it must focus on the substance of the bridge. Talk to the stones, the creators, if you don't, someone will build a new bridge and everything you have will collapse. If you lack direction appoint a Creator Council of YouTubers large and small from across the world and your platform and ask them questions.

Not guarded, vague questions but pointed questions that have meaning and will affect how you approach things, how you do things. Stop acting. Stop making. Stop managing. Listen and be seen to listen. If you don't, eventually, someone else will. You're the biggest because you were first not because you're the best, one day competition will be fierce and all the time you waste now will be to the detriment of yourselves, your creators and your audience but most importantly to your business, to all of your advertisers.

Get it right, make it strong or be replaced. That's entertainment.

Good luck,

M

snippet.textDisplay: Rewind is a party, a part of a celebration that we all, as a youtuber made it this far in a 1 year period, and created a great video and take participation in Youtube. And Youtube right now took the meaning of rewind as "A literal rewind". They took it as a real rewind, which means only going back, seeing popular things. And not partying. They are not celebrating at this point. They took rewind as a routinity, and not for fun and excitement. Look at how good those rewinds used to be. Why? Because youtube didn't use to make a video of rewind only for routinity. They made it to give us a moment to appreciate everything in a year in youtube, and give us a moment to celebrate how far we have made it. This is the point of view from youtube. From "Hey, I have an idea! Lets make compilations of things from the beginning of the year, until its ending." To: "Geez. The year is ending. Now we need to make a rewind again."

I think that the big complaint people have about Rewind is that it doesn't summarize "the YouTube I watch". In particular, a Western, English-speaking YouTube with a particular emphasis on your personal interests.

No individual's YouTube experience represents the platform. There are a lot more people here that are different from you, and not part of your particular community.

The personalized homepage makes it feel like the site is made for you, but it's a much more diverse place than people want to accept.

snippet.textDisplay:
The one thing I hate more than anything else is willful ignorance. That's why people like antivaxers, climate change deniers, and flat Earthers are, in my eyes, some of the lowest "humans" there are: because the only way anyone could continue to think that way is if they willfully disregarded all the overwhelmingly vast evidence to the contrary because it didn't suit their views. But then we have situations like this where a big organisation pretends its flaws don't exist or aren't their problem. That kind of willful ignorance is just sad. I respect people who acknowledge their flaws and try to fix them. Those are some of the best individuals humanity has to offer because when no one can achieve perfection, the next best thing we can do is try to improve as much as possible. But big corporations like YouTube are cowards. They do whatever they think will make them look good and make them money with the least amount of problems. And that kind of approach is what kills innovation, or at least it kills worth-while innovation. That kind of thinking just leads to a world full of bland nothingness and nothing worth actually spending time on. But I suppose you can't really blame the corporations, either. In the society we've built, that kind of thinking is the only way for big companies to stay alive. No matter what you do, someone somewhere will find some way to exploit the law against you, even if they mean well in the end, so the only safe thing to do is to follow the law to the letter. And that's the problem: the law is boring, bland, and unimaginative, not to mention how convoluted it can be. That's why lawyers are paid so well: no one in their right mind would want to deal with that nonsense if it didn't involve a huge payoff. Not to mention the fact that YouTube has to manage multiple sets of laws, forcing it to adopt the strictest policies to make sure it doesn't violate any of them, which leaves them even less room to be creative.


[End of 1:30 AM ramble.]
